ccWlanIndex.name: ccWlanIndex
ccWlanIndex.description: Simple index. (In the ccRfSum tables, entry 1001 is used to represent the roll-up of all RF communications on this switch).

ccWlanSubnet.name: ccWlanSubnet
ccWlanSubnet.description: The subnet/LAN this WLAN is associated with. If not associated with any subnet/LAN, this value will be 0.

ccWlanPortalsAdopted.name: ccWlanPortalsAdopted
ccWlanPortalsAdopted.description: Pointer to portal(s) adopted by this WLAN.

ccWlanDisallowMuToMu.name: ccWlanDisallowMuToMu
ccWlanDisallowMuToMu.description: Set to true to prohibit MU-to-MU communication.

ccWlanMuAclDefault.name: ccWlanMuAclDefault
ccWlanMuAclDefault.description: Describes the default behavior if none of this WLAN's ccWlanMuAclTable entries match the MAC address of an MU attempting to associate with this WLAN.

ccWlanAuthentication.name: ccWlanAuthentication
ccWlanAuthentication.description: If auth802dot1xEap, additional EAP settings for this WLAN will be used from the matching entry in the ccWlanAuthEapTable. Likewise, if authKerberos, use the settings in the matching entry in the ccWlanAuthKerberosTable.

ccWlanEncryption.name: ccWlanEncryption
ccWlanEncryption.description: If cryptoWep40 or cryptoWep128, additional WEP settings for this WLAN will be used from the matching entry in the ccWlanCryptoWepTable. Likewise, if cryptoWpaTkip, use the settings in the matching entry in the ccWlanCryptoWpaTable. Likewise, if cryptoKeyguardMcm, use the settings in the matching entry in the ccWlanCryptoKeyguardTable.

ccWlanWeight.name: ccWlanWeight
ccWlanWeight.description: The weight to be used when QoS for all WLANs is set to weighted-round-robin. Note that the sum of all weights across all WLANs need not total 100.

ccWlanAuthEapTable.name: ccWlanAuthEapTable
ccWlanAuthEapTable.description: Table of EAP authentication settings for each WLAN.

ccWlanAuthEapRadius1Server.name: ccWlanAuthEapRadius1Server
ccWlanAuthEapRadius1Server.description: IP address of the primary RADIUS server.

ccWlanAuthEapRadius1Port.name: ccWlanAuthEapRadius1Port
ccWlanAuthEapRadius1Port.description: Port number of the primary RADIUS server.

ccWlanAuthEapRadius1SharedSecret.name: ccWlanAuthEapRadius1SharedSecret
ccWlanAuthEapRadius1SharedSecret.description: Shared secret of the primary RADIUS server.

ccWlanAuthEapRadius2Server.name: ccWlanAuthEapRadius2Server
ccWlanAuthEapRadius2Server.description: IP address of the secondary RADIUS server.

ccWlanAuthEapRadius2Port.name: ccWlanAuthEapRadius2Port
ccWlanAuthEapRadius2Port.description: Port number of the secondary RADIUS server.

ccWlanAuthEapRadius2SharedSecret.name: ccWlanAuthEapRadius2SharedSecret
ccWlanAuthEapRadius2SharedSecret.description: Shared secret of the secondary RADIUS server.

ccWlanAuthKerberosTable.name: ccWlanAuthKerberosTable
ccWlanAuthKerberosTable.description: Table of Kerberos authentication settings for each WLAN.

ccWlanCryptoWepTable.name: ccWlanCryptoWepTable
ccWlanCryptoWepTable.description: Table of WEP encryption settings for each WLAN.

ccWlanCryptoWepPassKey.name: ccWlanCryptoWepPassKey
ccWlanCryptoWepPassKey.description: Pass key. If this value is written, the four WepKey1..4 will be overwritten.

ccWlanCryptoWepKey1.name: ccWlanCryptoWepKey1
ccWlanCryptoWepKey1.description: WEP key #1 exactly 13 octets for WEP-128 (104-bit key); exactly 5 octets for WEP-64 (40-bit key).

ccWlanCryptoWepKey2.name: ccWlanCryptoWepKey2
ccWlanCryptoWepKey2.description: WEP key #2 exactly 13 octets for WEP-128 (104-bit key); exactly 5 octets for WEP-64 (40-bit key).

ccWlanCryptoWepKey3.name: ccWlanCryptoWepKey3
ccWlanCryptoWepKey3.description: WEP key #3 exactly 13 octets for WEP-128 (104-bit key); exactly 5 octets for WEP-64 (40-bit key).

ccWlanCryptoWepKey4.name: ccWlanCryptoWepKey4
ccWlanCryptoWepKey4.description: WEP key #4 exactly 13 octets for WEP-128 (104-bit key); exactly 5 octets for WEP-64 (40-bit key).

ccWlanCryptoWepKeyToUse.name: ccWlanCryptoWepKeyToUse
ccWlanCryptoWepKeyToUse.description: Specifies which WEP key to use.

ccWlanCryptoWpaTable.name: ccWlanCryptoWpaTable
ccWlanCryptoWpaTable.description: Table of WPA-TKIP encryption settings for each WLAN.

ccWlanCryptoWpaKeyRotationInterval.name: ccWlanCryptoWpaKeyRotationInterval
ccWlanCryptoWpaKeyRotationInterval.description: Broadcast key rotation, (if enabled), occurs every this many seconds.

ccWlanCryptoKeyguardTable.name: ccWlanCryptoKeyguardTable
ccWlanCryptoKeyguardTable.description: Table of KeyGuard-MCM encryption settings for each WLAN.

ccWlanCryptoKeyguardKeyToUse.name: ccWlanCryptoKeyguardKeyToUse
ccWlanCryptoKeyguardKeyToUse.description: Specifies which WEP key to use.

ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoTable.name: ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoTable
ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoTable.description: Table of WPA-CCMP encryption settings for each WLAN.

ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoKeyRotationInterval.name: ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoKeyRotationInterval
ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoKeyRotationInterval.description: Broadcast key rotation, (if enabled), occurs every this many seconds.

ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoAllowTkipClient.name: ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoAllowTkipClient
ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoAllowTkipClient.description: WPA2-CCMP Mixed Mode enables WPA2-CCMP and WPA-TKIP Clients to operate simultaneously on the network. Enabling this option allows backwards compatiblity for clients that support WPA-TKIP but do not support WPA2-CCMP.

ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoFastRoamPreAuth.name: ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoFastRoamPreAuth
ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoFastRoamPreAuth.description: Enabling this option enables a client associated with one Access Port to carry out an 802.1x authentication with another Access Port before it roams over to it. The WS2000 will cache the keying information of the client until it roams to the new Access Port. This enables the roaming the client to start sending and receiving data sooner by not having to do 802.1x authentication after it roams. Note: This option only works when 802.1x authentication is enabled for the WLAN.

ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoFastRoamKeyCache.name: ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoFastRoamKeyCache
ccWlanCryptoWpaTwoFastRoamKeyCache.description: This option enables the WS2000 to use a Pairwise Master Key (PMK) derived with a client on one Access Port, with the same client when it roams over to another Access Port. Upon roaming the client does not have to do 802.1x authentication and can start sending/receiving data sooner. Note: This option only works when 802.1x authentication is enabled for the WLAN.

ccWlanSigStatsTable.name: ccWlanSigStatsTable
ccWlanSigStatsTable.description: This table describes statistics about RSSI, Signal, Noise, and SNR for packets recieved via each WLAN on the switch.

ccWlanSigStatsNumPkts.name: ccWlanSigStatsNumPkts
ccWlanSigStatsNumPkts.description: Total packets received included in all the other counters reported in this row.

ccWlanSigStatsSignalBest.name: ccWlanSigStatsSignalBest
ccWlanSigStatsSignalBest.description: The best Signal value seen so far. (Remember that a -20dBm Signal is better than -60dBm). This value is initialized to -500dBm.

ccWlanSigStatsSignalWorst.name: ccWlanSigStatsSignalWorst
ccWlanSigStatsSignalWorst.description: The worst Signal value seen so far. (Remember that a -80dBm Signal is worse than -60dBm). This value is initialized to 500dBm.

ccWlanSigStatsSignalSum.name: ccWlanSigStatsSignalSum
ccWlanSigStatsSignalSum.description: A running sum of all Signal values calculated by the switch (using reported RSSI values), for packets received. Note that this value is normally a negative value ranging from -10dBm to -80dBm. It is possible for this value to be positive, but that would be rare, and would signal an exceptionally strong signal.

ccWlanSigStatsSignalSumSquares.name: ccWlanSigStatsSignalSumSquares
ccWlanSigStatsSignalSumSquares.description: A sum of the squares of each Signal value calculated for packets received. Unlike _SignalSum, this value is never negative, since the square of a negative number is a positive.

ccWlanSigStatsNoiseBest.name: ccWlanSigStatsNoiseBest
ccWlanSigStatsNoiseBest.description: The best Noise value seen so far. (Remember that -80dBm Noise is better than -70dBm). This value is initialized to 500dBm.

ccWlanSigStatsNoiseWorst.name: ccWlanSigStatsNoiseWorst
ccWlanSigStatsNoiseWorst.description: The worst Noise value seen so far. (Remember that -50dBm Noise is worse than -60dBm). This value is initialized to -500dBm.

ccWlanSigStatsNoiseSum.name: ccWlanSigStatsNoiseSum
ccWlanSigStatsNoiseSum.description: A running sum of all Noise values calculated by the switch (using reported RSSI values), for packets. Like _SignalSum, this value is normally a negative value.

ccWlanSigStatsNoiseSumSquares.name: ccWlanSigStatsNoiseSumSquares
ccWlanSigStatsNoiseSumSquares.description: A sum of the squares of each Noise value calculated for packets received. As with _SignalSumSquares, this value is never negative.

ccWlanSigStatsSnrBest.name: ccWlanSigStatsSnrBest
ccWlanSigStatsSnrBest.description: The best SNR value seen so far. (Remember that +30dBm SNR is better than +20dBm). This value is initialized to -500dB.

ccWlanSigStatsSnrWorst.name: ccWlanSigStatsSnrWorst
ccWlanSigStatsSnrWorst.description: The worst SNR value seen so far. (Remember that +10dBm SNR is worse than +20dBm). This value is initialized to 500dB.

ccWlanSigStatsSnrSum.name: ccWlanSigStatsSnrSum
ccWlanSigStatsSnrSum.description: A running sum of all SNR values calculated by the switch (using reported RSSI values), for packets received. Unlike _Signal and _Noise, this value is never negative.

ccWlanSigStatsSnrSumSquares.name: ccWlanSigStatsSnrSumSquares
ccWlanSigStatsSnrSumSquares.description: A sum of the squares of each SNR value calculated for packets received. This value is never negative.

ccWlanSumStatsShortTable.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortTable
ccWlanSumStatsShortTable.description: Averages and rates calculated over the SHORT window for each WLAN.

ccWlanSumStatsShortTimestamp.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortTimestamp
ccWlanSumStatsShortTimestamp.description: Snapshot of sysUpTime as of the END of the 'window' of time that this entry of values represents.

ccWlanSumStatsShortNumPkts.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortNumPkts
ccWlanSumStatsShortNumPkts.description: The number of packets used to calculate the statistics in this window.

ccWlanSumStatsShortPktsPerSec100.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortPktsPerSec100
ccWlanSumStatsShortPktsPerSec100.description: Packets per second as averaged over the 'window'. For transmitted packets, each packet sucessfully sent counts as 1, (not N, where N is the number of retries). Since SNMP does not convey decimal values, the result is multiplied by 100.

ccWlanSumStatsShortPktsPerSecTx100.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortPktsPerSecTx100
ccWlanSumStatsShortPktsPerSecTx100.description: Packets per second TX as averaged over the 'window'. Each packet sucessfully sent counts as 1, (not N, where N is the number of retries). Since SNMP does not convey decimal values, the result is multiplied by 100.

ccWlanSumStatsShortPktsPerSecRx100.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortPktsPerSecRx100
ccWlanSumStatsShortPktsPerSecRx100.description: Packets per second RX as averaged over the 'window'. Since SNMP does not convey decimal values, the result is multiplied by 100.

ccWlanSumStatsShortThroughput.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortThroughput
ccWlanSumStatsShortThroughput.description: Actual number of bits sent and received over the window, divided by the number of seconds in the window. For transmitted packets, each packet sucessfully sent counts as 1, (not N, where N is the number of retries).

ccWlanSumStatsShortThroughputTx.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortThroughputTx
ccWlanSumStatsShortThroughputTx.description: Actual number of bits TX over the window, divided by the number of seconds in the window. Each packet sucessfully sent counts as 1, (not N, where N is the number of retries).

ccWlanSumStatsShortThroughputRx.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortThroughputRx
ccWlanSumStatsShortThroughputRx.description: Actual number of bits RX over the window, divided by the number of seconds in the window.

ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgBitSpeed.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgBitSpeed
ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgBitSpeed.description: An octet-weighted average of the speeds of all packets sent/received. (For each possible speed, multiply the number of octets sent/received by that speed; divide the sum by the total number of octets; multiply by 8). For transmitted packets, each packet sucessfully sent counts as 1, (not N, where N is the number of retries). This can be said in more plain english as: the average bit-speed at which packets were sent/received.

ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgMuSignal.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgMuSignal
ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgMuSignal.description: The average of all signal values over the window. NOTE: dBm are normally negative. Here the NEGATIVE values are reported as POSITIVE values. PO

ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgMuNoise.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgMuNoise
ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgMuNoise.description: The average of all noise values over the window.

ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgMuSnr.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgMuSnr
ccWlanSumStatsShortAvgMuSnr.description: The average of all SNR values over the window.

ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kNUcastPkts.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kNUcastPkts
ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kNUcastPkts.description: Ratio of packets that were NOT unicast. Expressed as parts-per-10000.

ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kTxWithRetries.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kTxWithRetries
ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kTxWithRetries.description: Ratio of TX packets that experienced one or more retries. Expressed as parts-per-10000.

ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kDropped.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kDropped
ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kDropped.description: Packets dropped divided by packets sent. Dropped here means dropped intentionally due to the appropriate QoS queue being full. Other reasons for dropped packets are not counted in this ratio.

ccWlanSumStatsShortTxAvgRetries100.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortTxAvgRetries100
ccWlanSumStatsShortTxAvgRetries100.description: For all transmit packets (those that experienced some retries, those that were successfully transmitted with only 1 transmission, and those that attempted max times and gave-up), the average number of RE-transmission attempts. Said another (though identical) way: the sum of all tranmission attempts divided by the number of unique packets attempted to be sent. Since SNMP does not convey decimal values, the result above is multiplied by 100. If there were no RE-transmissions, this value would be 0. If every single packet required exactly two tranmissions, this value would be 100, (representing 1.00).

ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kRxUndecrypt.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kRxUndecrypt
ccWlanSumStatsShortPp10kRxUndecrypt.description: Ratio of RX packets that were undecryptable. Expressed as parts-per-10000.

ccWlanSumStatsShortTotalMus.name: ccWlanSumStatsShortTotalMus
ccWlanSumStatsShortTotalMus.description: The number of packets used to calculate the statistics in this window for all MUs associated with WLAN.

ccWlanSumStatsLongTable.name: ccWlanSumStatsLongTable
ccWlanSumStatsLongTable.description: Averages and rates calculated over the LONG window for each WLAN. (Refer to ccWlanSumStatsShortTable for descriptions).

ccWanTable.name: ccWanTable
ccWanTable.description: Table of WAN interfaces. There is only one WAN interface on the WS2000, but we show the WAN interface in a table for consistancy and to have an entry to point to from other tables, (such as the MatrixSrc and MatrixDest tables).

ccWanDhcpEnable.name: ccWanDhcpEnable
ccWanDhcpEnable.description: Enable DHCP on this WAN interface.

ccWanDhcpIpAddr.name: ccWanDhcpIpAddr
ccWanDhcpIpAddr.description: The IP address obtained via DHCP. If DHCP is disabled or if DHCP has not yet obtained values, this value will be 0.0.0.0.

ccWanDhcpSubnetMask.name: ccWanDhcpSubnetMask
ccWanDhcpSubnetMask.description: The subnet mask address obtained via DHCP. If DHCP is disabled or if DHCP has not yet obtained values, this value will be 0.0.0.0.

ccWanDhcpDefaultGateway.name: ccWanDhcpDefaultGateway
ccWanDhcpDefaultGateway.description: The default gateway obtained via DHCP. If DHCP is disabled or if DHCP has not yet obtained values, this value will be 0.0.0.0.

ccWanDhcpPrimaryDnsServer.name: ccWanDhcpPrimaryDnsServer
ccWanDhcpPrimaryDnsServer.description: The primary DNS server obtained via DHCP. If DHCP is disabled or if DHCP has not yet obtained values, this value will be 0.0.0.0.

ccWanDhcpSecondaryDnsServer.name: ccWanDhcpSecondaryDnsServer
ccWanDhcpSecondaryDnsServer.description: The secondary DNS server obtained via DHCP. If DHCP is disabled or if DHCP has not yet obtained values, this value will be 0.0.0.0.

ccWanSubnetMask.name: ccWanSubnetMask
ccWanSubnetMask.description: The subnet mask to use if DHCP is not enabled. If DHCP is enabled, this value is still writeable, but is not used.

ccWanDefaultGateway.name: ccWanDefaultGateway
ccWanDefaultGateway.description: The default gateway to use if DHCP is not enabled. If DHCP is enabled, this value is still writeable, but is not used.

ccWanPrimaryDnsServer.name: ccWanPrimaryDnsServer
ccWanPrimaryDnsServer.description: The primary DNS server to use if DHCP is not enabled. If DHCP is enabled, this value is still writeable, but is not used.

ccWanSecondaryDnsServer.name: ccWanSecondaryDnsServer
ccWanSecondaryDnsServer.description: The secondary DNS server to use if DHCP is not enabled. If DHCP is enabled, this value is still writeable, but is not used.

ccWanPppoeEnable.name: ccWanPppoeEnable
ccWanPppoeEnable.description: Enable PPPoE for this WAN interface.

ccWanPppoePassword.name: ccWanPppoePassword
ccWanPppoePassword.description: PPPoE password. When this value is read, the switch returns a DisplayString of zero length.

ccWanPppoeAuthType.name: ccWanPppoeAuthType
ccWanPppoeAuthType.description: PPPoE authentication type. If no bits are set, no authentication is done. If more than one bit is set, any of the selected methods may be used by the switch.

ccWanIpAddrTable.name: ccWanIpAddrTable
ccWanIpAddrTable.description: Table of IP addresses for the given WAN interface. Up to 8 IP addresses per WAN interface.

ccWanIpAddrIndex.name: ccWanIpAddrIndex
ccWanIpAddrIndex.description: Simple index 1..8 of entries for each WAN interface.

ccWanFirewallGlobalEnable.name: ccWanFirewallGlobalEnable
ccWanFirewallGlobalEnable.description: This variable enables/disables the global state of the firewall. Note that if the firewall function is disabled, NAT, VPN, content filtering and subnet access are also disabled. (Disabling all these functions would only be useful in using the WS2000 in an existing network topology). Factory-default state is TRUE.

ccWanFirewallTable.name: ccWanFirewallTable
ccWanFirewallTable.description: Table of Firewall attacks that can be enabled/disabled.

ccWanFirewallIndex.name: ccWanFirewallIndex
ccWanFirewallIndex.description: Simple index, but with explicitly enumerated values.

ccWanFirewallDescription.name: ccWanFirewallDescription
ccWanFirewallDescription.description: Short description of the type of attack.

ccWanFirewallAlwaysEnabled.name: ccWanFirewallAlwaysEnabled
ccWanFirewallAlwaysEnabled.description: A few of the firewall algorithms can NOT be disabled. If this value is TRUE, this is one of those algorithms. Any attempt to set ccWanFwEnable to FALSE will result in a BAD-VALUE error.

ccWanFirewallEnable.name: ccWanFirewallEnable
ccWanFirewallEnable.description: Set to TRUE to enable this type of firewall check.

ccWanFirewallMimeFloodMaxHeaderLength.name: ccWanFirewallMimeFloodMaxHeaderLength
ccWanFirewallMimeFloodMaxHeaderLength.description: Mime flood attack check max header length.

ccWanFirewallMimeFloodMaxHeaders.name: ccWanFirewallMimeFloodMaxHeaders
ccWanFirewallMimeFloodMaxHeaders.description: Mime flood attack check max headers.

ccWanNatLowestUnusedSlot.name: ccWanNatLowestUnusedSlot
ccWanNatLowestUnusedSlot.description: Since the ccWanNatTable is actually implemented as a single list of entries, the second index of the ccWanNatTable, (ccWanNatIndex), must be unique across all ccWanNatTable entries. This scalar tells the network management software the lowest unused value that is available to be used for ccWanNatIndex, when creating a new ccWanNatTable entry.

ccWanNatTable.name: ccWanNatTable
ccWanNatTable.description: Table of NAT mappings for each IP address assigned to each WAN interface. (The WS2000 currently only has one WAN interface, but all MIBs are designed for the possibility of multiple WAN interfaces).

ccWanNatIndex.name: ccWanNatIndex
ccWanNatIndex.description: Simple index matching the simple index in the ccWanTable.

ccWanNatWanIpAddress.name: ccWanNatWanIpAddress
ccWanNatWanIpAddress.description: One, (of possibly several), IP addresses assigned to this WAN interface. One entries in this table will appear for each matching entry in the ccWanIpAddrTable.

ccWanNatType.name: ccWanNatType
ccWanNatType.description: Configure the NAT type. Only if 'nat1to1' is selected is the ccWanNat1to1IpAddr value is used. In such a case, any corresponding entries in the ccWanNatInboundTable and the ccWanNatOutboundTable are ignored. If 'none' is selected, all the above mentioned values are ignored. If '1toMany' is selected, the ccWanNat1to1IpAddr value is ignored, but entries, (if any), in the two tables are relevant.

ccWanNat1to1IpAddr.name: ccWanNat1to1IpAddr
ccWanNat1to1IpAddr.description: The IP address to use for outbound 1-to-1 mapping. Only used if ccWanNatType is '1to1'.

ccWanNatInboundDefaultEna.name: ccWanNatInboundDefaultEna
ccWanNatInboundDefaultEna.description: If set, any port that is NOT found in the ccWanNatInboundTable entries is forwarded to the IP addr specified by ccWanNatInboundDefaultIp.

ccWanNatInboundDefaultIp.name: ccWanNatInboundDefaultIp
ccWanNatInboundDefaultIp.description: IP addr to send ports that do not match any entry in the ccWanNatInboundTable.

ccWanNatInboundTable.name: ccWanNatInboundTable
ccWanNatInboundTable.description: Table of inbound NAT mappings for IP addresses on WAN interfaces that are set to ccWanNatType of '1to1' or '1toMany'.

ccWanNatInboundIndex.name: ccWanNatInboundIndex
ccWanNatInboundIndex.description: A given IP address on a given WAN interface may have many inbound NAT mappings. This (3rd) index numbers those many mappings.

ccWanNatInboundTransport.name: ccWanNatInboundTransport
ccWanNatInboundTransport.description: Transport for which this mapping applies.

ccWanNatOutboundTable.name: ccWanNatOutboundTable
ccWanNatOutboundTable.description: Table of outbound NAT mappings for IP addresses on WAN interfaces that are set to ccWanNatType of '1toMany'.

ccWanNatOutboundSubnetIndex.name: ccWanNatOutboundSubnetIndex
ccWanNatOutboundSubnetIndex.description: A different mapping can be set for each subnet. This (3rd) index specifies the subnet. This index is the same value for a given subnet as in the ccLanTable.

ccWanNatOutboundPossibleIpAddr.name: ccWanNatOutboundPossibleIpAddr

ccWanNatOutboundIpAddr.name: ccWanNatOutboundIpAddr
ccWanNatOutboundIpAddr.description: This value points to the ccWanIpAddrTable entry that has been selected for the outbound NAT mapping.

ccWanVpnRemoteSubnet.name: ccWanVpnRemoteSubnet
ccWanVpnRemoteSubnet.description: IP addr of the remote subnet.

ccWanVpnRemoteGateway.name: ccWanVpnRemoteGateway
ccWanVpnRemoteGateway.description: Gateway IP addr for the remote subnet.

ccWanVpnKeyExchange.name: ccWanVpnKeyExchange

ccWanVpnKeyManualTable.description: Table of Manual Key Setting entries.

ccWanVpnKeyManualAhAuth.description: data authentication and anti-replay services for the VPN tunnel. The following 2 keys have max length: md5 - 32 hex characters sha1 - 40

ccWanVpnKeyManualInAhAuthKey.name: ccWanVpnKeyManualInAhAuthKey
ccWanVpnKeyManualInAhAuthKey.description: AH Authentication Key for inbound traffic.

ccWanVpnKeyManualOutAhAuthKey.name: ccWanVpnKeyManualOutAhAuthKey

ccWanVpnKeyManualOutAhSpi.name: ccWanVpnKeyManualOutAhSpi

ccWanVpnKeyManualEspType.description: packet encryption and optional data authentication and anti-replay services for the VPN tunnel. Some of the next 6 variables are used depending on: none - all 6 variables are ignored esp - first 3 are used, next 3 ignored espWithAuth - all 6 are used

ccWanVpnKeyManualEspEncrypAlg.description: ESP Encryption Algorithm. The following 2 keys have max length: des - 16 hex characters des3 - 48 aes128bit - 32 aes192bit - 48 aes256bit - 64

ccWanVpnKeyManualInEspEncrypKey.name: ccWanVpnKeyManualInEspEncrypKey
ccWanVpnKeyManualInEspEncrypKey.description: ESP Encryption Key for inbound traffic.

ccWanVpnKeyManualOutEspEncrypKey.name: ccWanVpnKeyManualOutEspEncrypKey
ccWanVpnKeyManualOutEspEncrypKey.description: ESP Encryption Key for inbound traffic.

ccWanVpnKeyManualInEspAuthKey.description: ESP Authentication Key for inbound traffic.

ccWanVpnKeyManualOutEspAuthKey.description: ESP Authentication Key for outbound traffic.

ccWanVpnKeyManualInEspSpi.description: inbound security association created by the ESP algorithm.

ccWanVpnKeyManualOutEspSpi.name: ccWanVpnKeyManualOutEspSpi
ccWanVpnKeyManualOutEspSpi.description: outbound security association created by the ESP algorithm.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoTable.description: Table of Auto Key Setting entries.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoAhAuth.description: data authentication and anti-replay services for the VPN tunnel.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoEspType.description: packet encryption and optional data authentication and anti-replay services for the VPN tunnel. ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeOperationMode.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeOperationMode
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeOperationMode.description: IKE opreational mode. IKE main mode refers to the identity-protection exchange, and IKE aggressive mode refers to the aggressive exchange

ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeLocalIdType.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeLocalIdType
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeLocalIdType.description: type of ID to be used for the WS 2000 end of the SA. The next variable only applies if this is set to 'fqdn' or 'ufqdn'.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeLocalIdData.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeLocalIdData
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeLocalIdData.description: Based upon the Local ID type you gave, specify the FQDN or UFQDN,

ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeRemoteIdType.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeRemoteIdType
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeRemoteIdType.description: type of ID to be used for the remote end of the SA. The next variable only applies if this is set to 'fqdn' or 'ufqdn'.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeRemoteIdData.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeRemoteIdData
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeRemoteIdData.description: Based upon the Remote ID type you gave, specify the FQDN or UFQDN.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeAuthPassphrase.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeAuthPassphrase
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeAuthPassphrase.description: With Pre-Shared Key as the authentication mode, provide a key. MD5 : 32-character hexadecimal key. SHA1 : 40-character hexadecimal key.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeXauthMode.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeXauthMode
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeXauthMode.description: Currently XAUTH mechanism is not supported by WS2000 version 2.0. If 'none', the next 2 variables are ignored.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeXauthUsername.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeXauthUsername
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeXauthUsername.description: Currently XAUTH mechanism is not supported by WS2000 version 2.0.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeXauthPassword.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeXauthPassword
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeXauthPassword.description: Currently XAUTH mechanism is not supported by WS2000 version 2.0.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeKeyLifetime.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeKeyLifetime
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeKeyLifetime.description: The number of seconds that the key is valid.

ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeDiffieHelmanGroup.name: ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeDiffieHelmanGroup
ccWanVpnKeyAutoIkeDiffieHelmanGroup.description: The Diffie-Hellman key agreement protocol allows two users to exchange a secret key over an insecure medium without any prior secrets.

ccWanVpnSaTable.name: ccWanVpnSaTable
ccWanVpnSaTable.description: Status of all tunnels that have been configured on the switch.

ccWanVpnSaStatus.name: ccWanVpnSaStatus
ccWanVpnSaStatus.description: Status of each of the configured tunnels. When the tunnel is not in use the status will read NOT_ACTIVE. When the tunnel is connected the status will read ACTIVE.

ccWanVpnSaInSpi.name: ccWanVpnSaInSpi
ccWanVpnSaInSpi.description: Inbound SPI Security Parameter Index (SPI) for each of the tunnels. This is used locally by the switch to identify a security association. There are unique outbound and inbound SPIs.

ccWanVpnSaOutSpi.name: ccWanVpnSaOutSpi
ccWanVpnSaOutSpi.description: Outbound Security Parameter Index (SPI) for each of the tunnels. This is used locally by the switch to identify a security association. There are unique outbound and inbound SPIs.

ccWanVpnSaLifetime.name: ccWanVpnSaLifetime
ccWanVpnSaLifetime.description: Lifetime associated with a particular Security Association (SA).

ccWanVpnSaTxBytes.name: ccWanVpnSaTxBytes
ccWanVpnSaTxBytes.description: Total number amount of data (in bytes) transmitted through each of the configured tunnels.

ccWanVpnSaRxBytes.name: ccWanVpnSaRxBytes
ccWanVpnSaRxBytes.description: Total number amount of data (in bytes) received through each of the configured tunnels.

ccWanVpnIkeTable.name: ccWanVpnIkeTable
ccWanVpnIkeTable.description: Table of tunnels configured to use IKE for automatic key exchange

ccWanVpnIkeState.name: ccWanVpnIkeState
ccWanVpnIkeState.description: State for each of the tunnels configured to use IKE for automatic key exchange. When the tunnel is not active this will display NOT_CONNECTED. When the tunnel is active this will display CONNECTED.

ccWanVpnIkeRemainingLife.name: ccWanVpnIkeRemainingLife
ccWanVpnIkeRemainingLife.description: Remaining life for the current IKE key for each of the listed tunnels.

ccWanContentBlockOutUrlTable.name: ccWanContentBlockOutUrlTable
ccWanContentBlockOutUrlTable.description: Table of Content Block URL entries.

ccPortTable.name: ccPortTable
ccPortTable.description: This table contains one entry for each physical port on the switch.

ccPortIndex.name: ccPortIndex
ccPortIndex.description: Simple index. Instance/index .1 represents the port labelled '1' on the physical unit. The WAN port will reside after all ports that are numbered on the physcial unit.

ccPortType.name: ccPortType
ccPortType.description: Indicates the type of the port.

ccPortPoeEquipped.name: ccPortPoeEquipped
ccPortPoeEquipped.description: Indicates the port can provide power-over-ethernet.

ccPortStatus.name: ccPortStatus
ccPortStatus.description: Tells if the port is up/down.

ccPortDuplex.name: ccPortDuplex
ccPortDuplex.description: Describes the duplex, (half/full), status of the port.

ccPortSpeed.name: ccPortSpeed
ccPortSpeed.description: Link's speed in bits per second.

ccSubnetIpSubnetMask.name: ccSubnetIpSubnetMask
ccSubnetIpSubnetMask.description: IPaddr subnet mask of this Subnet

ccSubnetPortMembers.name: ccSubnetPortMembers
ccSubnetPortMembers.description: Pointer to zero or more ports that are members of this Subnet. No port can be a member of more than one Subnet at any given time.

ccSubnetWlanMembers.name: ccSubnetWlanMembers
ccSubnetWlanMembers.description: Pointer to zero or more WLANs that are members of this Subnet. No Subnet can be a member of more than one Subnet at any given time.

ccSubnetDhcpState.name: ccSubnetDhcpState
ccSubnetDhcpState.description: Specifies how Subnet gets its IP address/mask.

ccSubnetDhcpIpAddress.name: ccSubnetDhcpIpAddress
ccSubnetDhcpIpAddress.description: The IP address obtained via DHCP if this Subnet is configured as a DHCP client. If this Subnet is configured to not use DHCP, or is a DHCP server this value will be 0.0.0.0. Likewise, if this Subnet is configured to be a DHCP client but has not yet obtained a value via DHCP, this value will be 0.0.0.0.

ccSubnetDhcpSubnetMask.name: ccSubnetDhcpSubnetMask
ccSubnetDhcpSubnetMask.description: The Subnet IPaddr subnet mask obtained via DHCP if this Subnet is configured as a DHCP client. If this Subnet is configured to not use DHCP, or is a DHCP server this value will be 0.0.0.0. Likewise, if this Subnet is configured to be a DHCP client but has not yet obtained a value via DHCP, this value will be 0.0.0.0.

ccSubnetDhcpServerTable.name: ccSubnetDhcpServerTable
ccSubnetDhcpServerTable.description: Configures a DHCP server for a Subnet. While these values can always be SET, they will only take effect if the given Subnet is enabled and configured to be a DHCP server.

ccSubnetDhcpServerEnable.name: ccSubnetDhcpServerEnable
ccSubnetDhcpServerEnable.description: Enable DHCP Server functionality on this Subnet.

ccSubnetDhcpServerPoolStart.name: ccSubnetDhcpServerPoolStart
ccSubnetDhcpServerPoolStart.description: The start/low end of the range of IP addresses to give-out.

ccSubnetDhcpServerPoolEnd.name: ccSubnetDhcpServerPoolEnd
ccSubnetDhcpServerPoolEnd.description: The end/high-end of the range of IP addresses to give-out.

ccSubnetDhcpServerPrimaryDns.name: ccSubnetDhcpServerPrimaryDns
ccSubnetDhcpServerPrimaryDns.description: IP address of primary DNS server to assign to DHCP clients.

ccSubnetDhcpServerSecondaryDns.name: ccSubnetDhcpServerSecondaryDns
ccSubnetDhcpServerSecondaryDns.description: IP address of secondary DNS server to assign to DHCP clients.

ccSubnetDhcpServerDefaultGateway.name: ccSubnetDhcpServerDefaultGateway
ccSubnetDhcpServerDefaultGateway.description: IP address of default gateway to assign to DHCP clients.

ccSubnetDhcpServerWinsServer.name: ccSubnetDhcpServerWinsServer
ccSubnetDhcpServerWinsServer.description: DHCP Server WINS server IP Address.

ccSubnetDhcpServerStaticMapTable.name: ccSubnetDhcpServerStaticMapTable
ccSubnetDhcpServerStaticMapTable.description: Table of static MAC-IPaddr mappings for the given DHCP server.

ccSubnetDhcpServerStaticMapIpAddr.name: ccSubnetDhcpServerStaticMapIpAddr
ccSubnetDhcpServerStaticMapIpAddr.description: IP address to assign to this MAC address.

ccSubnetAccessTable.name: ccSubnetAccessTable
ccSubnetAccessTable.description: Describes how packets are allowed to flow from different sources to different destinations. Note that since only subnets can be sources for this table, the ccSubnetTable:ccSubnetIndex is used as the 1st index to this table. Note that this table never contains entries where src==dest, for example, there is no entry with: _SrcPointerToSource points to subnet1 _DestPointerToSource points to subnet1 Note also that if a given subnet does not exisit, (because it has not been enabled in ccSubnetTable), no entries in this table will exist with that subnet as either src or dest.

ccSubnetAccessDestType.name: ccSubnetAccessDestType
ccSubnetAccessDestType.description: Type of the destination. destDrop is a 'virtual' destination that accounts for all dropped packets.

ccSubnetAccessDestPtrToDest.name: ccSubnetAccessDestPtrToDest
ccSubnetAccessDestPtrToDest.description: A pointer to the corresponding entry in the ccSubnet or ccWan table, (depending on _DestType).

ccSubnetAccessRuleType.name: ccSubnetAccessRuleType
ccSubnetAccessRuleType.description: All ccSubnetAccessRuleTable entries for this combination of ccSubnetIndex and ccSubnetAccessDestIndex will be of the same type, (accept or deny).

ccSubnetAccessPtrToRules.name: ccSubnetAccessPtrToRules
ccSubnetAccessPtrToRules.description: Points to the zero or more ccSubnetAccessRuleTable entries that correspond to this ccSubnetIndex + ccSubnetAccessDestIndex combination/entry. This value cannot be changed here, but is a reflection of the ccSubnetAccessRuleTable entries that currently point to this entry via their ccSubnetAccessRuleSrcPtr and _DestPtr values.

ccSubnetAccessRuleTable.name: ccSubnetAccessRuleTable
ccSubnetAccessRuleTable.description: Describes how packets are allowed to flow from different sources to different destinations. Note that since only subnets can be sources for this table, the ccSubnetTable:ccSubnetIndex is used as the 1st index to this table. Note that this table never contains entries where src==dest, for example, there is no entry with: _SrcPointerToSource points to subnet1 _DestPointerToSource points to subnet1 Note also that if a given subnet does not exisit, (because it has not been enabled in ccSubnetTable), no entries in this table will exist with that subnet as either src or dest.

ccSubnetAccessRuleIndex.name: ccSubnetAccessRuleIndex
ccSubnetAccessRuleIndex.description: Each src/dest combination can have several rules; this value is the index.

ccSubnetAccessRuleSrcPtr.name: ccSubnetAccessRuleSrcPtr
ccSubnetAccessRuleSrcPtr.description: This is the value of ccSubnetIndex corresponding to the source for this rule.

ccSubnetAccessRuleDestPtr.name: ccSubnetAccessRuleDestPtr
ccSubnetAccessRuleDestPtr.description: This is the value of ccSubnetAccessDestIndex corresponding to the destination for this rule.

ccSubnetAccessAdvInSrcIpLength.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvInSrcIpLength
ccSubnetAccessAdvInSrcIpLength.description: Mask length for the IP address

ccSubnetAccessAdvInDestIpLength.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvInDestIpLength
ccSubnetAccessAdvInDestIpLength.description: mask length for the IP address

ccSubnetAccessAdvInReverseNatIp.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvInReverseNatIp
ccSubnetAccessAdvInReverseNatIp.description: Address to use for reverse NAT. To disable, use 0.0.0.0.

ccSubnetAccessAdvInReverseNatPort.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvInReverseNatPort
ccSubnetAccessAdvInReverseNatPort.description: Port to use for reverse NAT.

ccSubnetAccessAdvInAction.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvInAction
ccSubnetAccessAdvInAction.description: Action on the acl i.e allow or deny

ccSubnetAccessAdvOutSrcIpLength.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvOutSrcIpLength
ccSubnetAccessAdvOutSrcIpLength.description: Mask length for the IP address

ccSubnetAccessAdvOutDestIpLength.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvOutDestIpLength
ccSubnetAccessAdvOutDestIpLength.description: mask length for the IP address

ccSubnetAccessAdvOutReverseNat.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvOutReverseNat
ccSubnetAccessAdvOutReverseNat.description: Points to a ccWanIpAddrTable entry representing the WAN IP addr to be used for NAT. To disable NAT, set this value to 0.

ccSubnetAccessAdvOutAction.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvOutAction
ccSubnetAccessAdvOutAction.description: Action on the acl i.e allow or deny

ccSubnetAccessAdvOverrideMode.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvOverrideMode
ccSubnetAccessAdvOverrideMode.description: Override the Subnet Access and NAT settings.

ccSubnetAccessAdvImportRules.name: ccSubnetAccessAdvImportRules
ccSubnetAccessAdvImportRules.description: When set to 1 the Subnet Access Rules shall be imported on top of the Advanced Access rules.

ccLanVlanType.name: ccLanVlanType
ccLanVlanType.description: Type of the VLAN port/user based

ccLanVlanTrunked.name: ccLanVlanTrunked
ccLanVlanTrunked.description: List of VLANs which are trunked.

ccLanVlanTable.name: ccLanVlanTable
ccLanVlanTable.description: Table of VLAN IDs mapped to Subnets.

ccRouterRip2SimplePassword.name: ccRouterRip2SimplePassword
ccRouterRip2SimplePassword.description: Password used for RIP v2 simple authentication.

ccRouterRip2Md5Key1Id.name: ccRouterRip2Md5Key1Id
ccRouterRip2Md5Key1Id.description: RIP v2 with MD5 authentication: key #1 - ID.

ccRouterRip2Md5Key1AuthKey.name: ccRouterRip2Md5Key1AuthKey
ccRouterRip2Md5Key1AuthKey.description: RIP v2 with MD5 authentication: key #1 - auth key.

ccRouterRip2Md5Key2Id.name: ccRouterRip2Md5Key2Id
ccRouterRip2Md5Key2Id.description: RIP v2 with MD5 authentication: key #2 - ID.

ccRouterRip2Md5Key2AuthKey.name: ccRouterRip2Md5Key2AuthKey
ccRouterRip2Md5Key2AuthKey.description: RIP v2 with MD5 authentication: key #2 - auth key.

ccRouterRoutesDestMask.name: ccRouterRoutesDestMask
ccRouterRoutesDestMask.description: Mask used to specify the route

ccRouterRoutesGateway.name: ccRouterRoutesGateway
ccRouterRoutesGateway.description: Ip address of the gateway for this route

ccRouterUserRoutesDestMask.name: ccRouterUserRoutesDestMask
ccRouterUserRoutesDestMask.description: Mask used to specify the route

ccRouterUserRoutesGateway.name: ccRouterUserRoutesGateway
ccRouterUserRoutesGateway.description: Ip address of the gateway for this route

ccRapPollSymbolMusEnable.name: ccRapPollSymbolMusEnable
ccRapPollSymbolMusEnable.description: Enable/disable polling MUs for their lists of known APs. The state of this variable persists across reboots. The factory-default state is disabled.

ccRapPollSymbolMusInterval.name: ccRapPollSymbolMusInterval
ccRapPollSymbolMusInterval.description: Amount of time to wait before polling the same MU for its known AP list again. Assuming the MU is disrupted for 3sec when it is polled, a value of 5min or more would interrupt MUs less than 1% of the time. The state of this variable persists across reboots. The factory-default state is 10 (minutes).

ccRapOnChannelEnable.name: ccRapOnChannelEnable
ccRapOnChannelEnable.description: Enable/disable polling MUs for their lists of known APs. The state of this variable persists across reboots. The factory-default state is disabled.

ccRapOnChannelInterval.name: ccRapOnChannelInterval
ccRapOnChannelInterval.description: Amount of time to wait before polling the same MU for its known AP list again. Assuming the MU is disrupted for 3sec when it is polled, a value of 5min or more would interrupt MUs less than 1% of the time. The state of this variable persists across reboots. The factory-default state is 10 (minutes).

ccRapDetectorsEnable.name: ccRapDetectorsEnable
ccRapDetectorsEnable.description: Enable/disable the entire 'detector' sub-system. On the true-to-false transition, any portals previously claimed as listeners will be released and reset. Once reset, they will appear to the switch as if just newly installed, (and thus may or may not be adopted depending on settings in the switch). The state of this variable persists across reboots. The factory-default state is disabled.

ccRapDetectorsInterval.name: ccRapDetectorsInterval
ccRapDetectorsInterval.description: Amount of time to wait before polling the same MU for its known AP list again. Assuming the MU is disrupted for 3sec when it is polled, a value of 5min or more would interrupt MUs less than 1% of the time. The state of this variable persists across reboots. The factory-default state is 10 (minutes).

ccRapAuthAllSymbolMac.name: ccRapAuthAllSymbolMac
ccRapAuthAllSymbolMac.description: If TRUE, any newly-discovered AP that has a MAC address with a Symbol vendor prefix is authorized, regardless of the ESSID.

ccRapAuthTable.name: ccRapAuthTable
ccRapAuthTable.description: A list of 'authorized' APs. There is no need to include on this list any APs adopted by the switch. Typically, this list will contain APs that are located in neighboring stores/buildings that are known by some means to NOT be rogue. So this is the List of APs that are Authorized and upon heard shall automatically be added to the Approved List instead of labelling them as Rogue APs. Note that this table persists across reboots.

ccRapAuthMacFilter.name: ccRapAuthMacFilter
ccRapAuthMacFilter.description: MAC address of AP to consider 'authorized'. To specify the entire MAC address as a wildcard, (match any MAC address), use FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF. (While it had been considered, it is NOT possible to wildcard just the vendor portion of the MAC).

ccRapAuthEssidFilter.name: ccRapAuthEssidFilter
ccRapAuthEssidFilter.description: ESSID of AP to consider 'authorized'. Set to 33 '*' characters for wildcard, (to match any ESSID). (ESSIDs must be 32ch or less).

ccRapAuthRowExists.name: ccRapAuthRowExists
ccRapAuthRowExists.description: A kludge to avoid RowStatus and save development time. Set this value to true when creating the row. Set this value to false to destroy the row. ??- better name.

ccRapAuthErase.name: ccRapAuthErase
ccRapAuthErase.description: Setting this value to TRUE erases all AuthTable entries.

ccRapAuthCopyAllApproved.name: ccRapAuthCopyAllApproved
ccRapAuthCopyAllApproved.description: Causes all ccRapResultsApprovedTable entries to be immediately copied to the ccRapAuthTable.

ccRapAuthCopyAllRogue.name: ccRapAuthCopyAllRogue
ccRapAuthCopyAllRogue.description: Causes all ccRapResultsRogueTable entries to be immediately copied to the ccRapAuthTable.

ccRapResultsApprovedAgeOut.name: ccRapResultsApprovedAgeOut
ccRapResultsApprovedAgeOut.description: If an entry in the _ResultsApproved table is not heard by any means for this number of minutes, is elligable to be removed from the table by the switch; (the switch, however, might not remove the entry until it gets around to it). A value of 0 indicates that entries will never be 'aged-out' of the table. The state of this variable persists across reboots. The factory-default state is 1 week, (10080 min).

ccRapResultsApprovedTable.name: ccRapResultsApprovedTable
ccRapResultsApprovedTable.description: Each AP MAC/ESSID combination heard by any enabled detection method will be reported in this table, if it has been determined to be 'approved' via one of the enabled methods controlled in ccAuth. Entries persist until that MAC/ESSID combination has not been heard for _AgeOut minutes.

ccRapResultsApprovedApMac.name: ccRapResultsApprovedApMac
ccRapResultsApprovedApMac.description: MAC address of the heard AP.

ccRapResultsApprovedCopyToAuthTable.name: ccRapResultsApprovedCopyToAuthTable
ccRapResultsApprovedCopyToAuthTable.description: When set to TRUE, this entry is copied to the RuleTable.

ccRapResultsApprovedFirstHeard.name: ccRapResultsApprovedFirstHeard
ccRapResultsApprovedFirstHeard.description: Snapshot of sysUpTime the first time this AP MAC/ESSID combination was heard by any Symbol MU.

ccRapResultsApprovedLastHeard.name: ccRapResultsApprovedLastHeard
ccRapResultsApprovedLastHeard.description: Snapshot of sysUpTime the most recent time this AP MAC/ESSID combination was heard by any Symbol MU.

ccRapResultsApprovedPortalPtr.name: ccRapResultsApprovedPortalPtr
ccRapResultsApprovedPortalPtr.description: A mask of Portal table entries. Those Portal entries indicated by a '1' in this mask were at one time the servicing Portal for an MU that reported hearing this AP. For a rogue of limited range in the parking lot on the north side of a store, it would be expected that only the Portals located in the north end of the store would be indicated by this mask, thus giving a rough indication of general direction of the rogue.

ccRapResultsApprovedHowFound.name: ccRapResultsApprovedHowFound
ccRapResultsApprovedHowFound.description: Describes the status of this AP. ??- I don't think we would report adoptedAp on the results table, so don't need this enum value.

ccRapResultsApprovedHowAuth.name: ccRapResultsApprovedHowAuth
ccRapResultsApprovedHowAuth.description: Describes how this AP was authorized, (or not). The order in which the various methods of authorizing APs is attempted is exactly the numerical order of the enums. ??- I deleted adoptedAp, since it seems to me that there is no good reason to report APs that this switch has adopted.

ccRapResultsApprovedChannel.name: ccRapResultsApprovedChannel
ccRapResultsApprovedChannel.description: Describes on which channel this AP was found.

ccRapResultsApprovedErase.name: ccRapResultsApprovedErase
ccRapResultsApprovedErase.description: Setting this value to TRUE erases all Results entries. Any APs heard after that event will be treated as newly heard; (which means they will also generate notifications, if enabled). ??- need 2nd scalar.

ccRapNewApprovedAp.name: ccRapNewApprovedAp
ccRapNewApprovedAp.description: A new AP has been heard that was in some manner authorized.

ccRapResultsRogueAgeOut.name: ccRapResultsRogueAgeOut
ccRapResultsRogueAgeOut.description: If an entry in the _ResultsRogue table is not heard by any means for this number of minutes, is elligable to be removed from the table by the switch; (the switch, however, might not remove the entry until it gets around to it). A value of 0 indicates that entries will never be 'aged-out' of the table. The state of this variable persists across reboots. The factory-default state is 1 week, (10080 min).

ccRapResultsRogueTable.name: ccRapResultsRogueTable
ccRapResultsRogueTable.description: Each AP MAC/ESSID combination heard by any enabled detection method will be reported in this table, if it has NOT been determined to be 'approved' via one of the enabled methods controlled in ccAuth. Entries persist until that MAC/ESSID combination has not been heard for _AgeOut minutes.

ccRapResultsRogueApMac.name: ccRapResultsRogueApMac
ccRapResultsRogueApMac.description: MAC address of the heard AP.

ccRapResultsRogueCopyToAuthTable.name: ccRapResultsRogueCopyToAuthTable
ccRapResultsRogueCopyToAuthTable.description: When set to TRUE, this entry is copied to the RuleTable.

ccRapResultsRogueFirstHeard.name: ccRapResultsRogueFirstHeard
ccRapResultsRogueFirstHeard.description: Snapshot of sysUpTime the first time this AP MAC/ESSID combination was heard by any Symbol MU.

ccRapResultsRogueLastHeard.name: ccRapResultsRogueLastHeard
ccRapResultsRogueLastHeard.description: Snapshot of sysUpTime the most recent time this AP MAC/ESSID combination was heard by any Symbol MU.

ccRapResultsRoguePortalPtr.name: ccRapResultsRoguePortalPtr
ccRapResultsRoguePortalPtr.description: A mask of Portal table entries. Those Portal entries indicated by a '1' in this mask were at one time the servicing Portal for an MU that reported hearing this AP. For a rogue of limited range in the parking lot on the north side of a store, it would be expected that only the Portals located in the north end of the store would be indicated by this mask, thus giving a rough indication of general direction of the rogue.

ccRapResultsRogueHowFound.name: ccRapResultsRogueHowFound
ccRapResultsRogueHowFound.description: Describes the status of this AP. ??- I don't think we would report adoptedAp on the results table, so don't need this enum value.

ccRapResultsRogueClosestPortalPtr.name: ccRapResultsRogueClosestPortalPtr
ccRapResultsRogueClosestPortalPtr.description: A pointer to closest reporting Portal to the Rogue AP, (where 'closest' is defined as greatest RSSI value among all Portals reporting this AP).

ccRapResultsRogueClosestPortalRssi.name: ccRapResultsRogueClosestPortalRssi
ccRapResultsRogueClosestPortalRssi.description: RSSI reported by the closest Portal.

ccRapResultsRogueChannel.name: ccRapResultsRogueChannel
ccRapResultsRogueChannel.description: Describes on which channel this AP was found.

ccRapResultsRogueErase.name: ccRapResultsRogueErase
ccRapResultsRogueErase.description: Setting this value to TRUE erases all Results entries. Any APs heard after that event will be treated as newly heard; (which means they will also generate notifications, if enabled). ??- need 2nd scalar.

ccRapNewRogueAp.name: ccRapNewRogueAp
ccRapNewRogueAp.description: A new AP has been heard that was NOT authorized.

ccRapPortalResultsApMac.name: ccRapPortalResultsApMac
ccRapPortalResultsApMac.description: The MAC address of the AP to be reported. (No wildcarding of the AP MAC is allowed. If it were, several APs could be found that match the selection criteria).

ccRapPortalResultsApEssid.name: ccRapPortalResultsApEssid
ccRapPortalResultsApEssid.description: The ESSID of the AP to be reported. (No wildcarding of the AP ESSID is allowed. If it were, several APs could be found that match the selection criteria).

ccRapPortalResultsInProcess.name: ccRapPortalResultsInProcess
ccRapPortalResultsInProcess.description: Setting to true erases the _PortalResultsTable, and immediately initiates a scan of all Portals currently enabled in ccRapControlOnChannel and ccRapControlDetectors. The switch does NOT wait until the next scan interval(s), but performs the scan immediately; (a human is most likely waiting for the results in mere seconds). Once the switch has completed scanning all enabled Portals, it sets this value to false.

ccRapPortalResultsTable.name: ccRapPortalResultsTable
ccRapPortalResultsTable.description: Each (enabled/configured) Portal that hears the specified AP's MAC/ESSID combination will be reported as one entry in this table. For a rogue of limited range in the parking lot on the north side of a store, it would be expected that only the Portals located in the north end of the store would be indicated by this mask, thus giving a rough indication of general direction of the rogue. Individual RSSI values combined with exact locations of the Portals can be used to triangulate the approximate position of the Rogue.

ccRapPortalResultsPortalMac.name: ccRapPortalResultsPortalMac
ccRapPortalResultsPortalMac.description: MAC address of the Portal reporting having heard the specified AP.

ccRapPortalResultsRssi.name: ccRapPortalResultsRssi
ccRapPortalResultsRssi.description: RSSI value heard by the Portal.

ccRapPollOneMuMac.name: ccRapPollOneMuMac
ccRapPollOneMuMac.description: Writing this value with the MAC address of a MU causes the switch to read that MU's known AP list. This read is performed just once, (it is not repeated). This read occurs regardless of the state of ccRapPollSymbolMusEnable. The read is also performed immediately - the switch does NOT wait until the next Sybmol MU poll interval, (as specified in ccRapPollSymbolMusInterval).

ccRapPollOneMuInProcess.name: ccRapPollOneMuInProcess
ccRapPollOneMuInProcess.description: Setting to true initiates the polling of one specified MU's known AP table. Once the switch receives a response from the requested MU, it sets this value to false. If the network management software sets this value to false, any future response from the MU will be ignored.

ccRapPollOneMuStatus.name: ccRapPollOneMuStatus
ccRapPollOneMuStatus.description: Describes if the MU is associated or not, and if so, if the MU is Symbol Rogue detect enabled or not.

ccRapPollOneMuResultsTable.name: ccRapPollOneMuResultsTable
ccRapPollOneMuResultsTable.description: Shows the known AP table as read from the specified MU. This table is NOT cumulative; that is, it only reflects exactly what was read from the most recent read of the specified MU's known AP table. If a non-Symbol MUs is specified, or if the MU is not currently associated with any Portal, the resulting table will be empty.

ccRapPollOneMuResultsRssi.name: ccRapPollOneMuResultsRssi
ccRapPollOneMuResultsRssi.description: RSSI reported for that known AP.

ccRapPollOneMuResultsApMac.name: ccRapPollOneMuResultsApMac
ccRapPollOneMuResultsApMac.description: MAC address of the heard AP.
